  "text": "The Earth's surface temperature rose by 0.6 ± 0.2°C over the 20 th century, with accelerated warming over the past two decades (IPCC, 2013) . With a warmer climate, the water holding capacity of the atmosphere and evaporation to the atmosphere increase (e.g. [CITATION_1] . Therefore, it would be expected that perturbation of the global water cycle would accompany global warming (e.g. [CITATION_2] . The possibility of increased precipitation intensity and variability is projected to boost the risk of extreme events such as typhoons/cyclones, droughts and floods (IPCC, 2013) . Many countries in temperate and tropical zones are vulnerable to such extreme events, exposing their coastal areas, including deltas, and their dense population to substantial human and economic consequences.",
